==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Churr
<hw>Churr</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Chirr</er>.]</ety> <def>A vibrant or whirring noise such as that
made by some insects, as the cockchafer, or by some birds, as the
nightjar, the partridge, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Churr</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Churr
<hw>Churr</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Churred</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Churr"ing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To make a churr, as a
cockchafer.</def></p>

<p><q>That's the <qex>churring</qex> of the nightjar.</q> <rj><qau>Hall
Caine.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Churr</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Churr
<hw>Churr</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To utter by churring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Churrus</ent>⟦br⟧
